{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524864"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:09:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:09:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14033"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14033"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.51,0.1,0.15,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6682"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53144"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6682"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14033"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38569"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"2921"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13792"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43468"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53144"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. She was diagnosed with autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD) five years ago. She has a medical history of hypertension, which is well-controlled. Her regular medication is telmisartan. She does not take any other medications. Her father, who also had ADPKD, died suddenly at the age of 50 due to an extra-renal manifestation of ADPKD. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation for screening this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stress echocardiography","Magnetic resonance angiography of the brain","Coronary angiography","Mercaptoacetyltriglycine (MAG-3) renal scan","Non-contrast computed tomography of the brain"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPatients with autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD) have an increased risk of intracranial aneurysms compared to the general population. The risk is particularly high in those with a family history of aneurysm or subarachnoid haemorrhage, as is likely the case with this patient whose father died suddenly from an extra-renal manifestation of ADPKD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance angiography of the brain\u003C/strong\u003E (MRA) is the most appropriate screening investigation for this patient. It provides detailed images of the cerebral vasculature and can detect intracranial aneurysms without exposing the patient to ionising radiation. Given the patient\u0027s family history, screening for intracranial aneurysms is warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStress echocardiography\u003C/strong\u003E is used to assess as an investigative tool for ischaemic heart disease and is not specifically indicated for ADPKD patients unless there are other cardiovascular risk factors or symptoms. \u003Cstrong\u003ECoronary angiography\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure used to diagnose coronary artery disease. It is not a screening test for ADPKD complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMAG-3 renal scan\u003C/strong\u003E is a specialised nuclear medicine scan used to assess renal function. It can detect obstructions in the urinary tract, evaluate blood flow to the kidneys and the drainage of urine from the kidneys to the bladder, and also assess differential renal function (in cases where one kidney may be underperforming compared to another). It has no specific role in ADPKD screening. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-contrast computed tomography of the brain\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide adequate information about the cerebral vasculature to detect aneurysms. Contrast-enhanced CT angiography could be an alternative to MRA, but MRA is preferred from perspectives of image quality and radiation exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn ADPKD patients, screening for intracranial aneurysms is recommended, especially in those with a family history of aneurysm or subarachnoid haemorrhage. Other important aspects of ADPKD management include blood pressure control, which this patient has achieved, and regular monitoring of renal function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD) have an increased risk of intracranial aneurysms.","MR angiography brain is the screening modality of choice."],"references":["Malhotra A, Wu X, Matouk CC, Forman HP, Gandhi D, Sanelli P. MR Angiography Screening and Surveillance for Intracranial Aneurysms in Autosomal Dominant Polycystic Kidney Disease: A Cost-effectiveness Analysis. Radiology. 2019 May;291(2):400\u20138."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38569"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14033"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38569"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-16T21:40:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-16T21:41:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data